        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<figure type="diagram"> 
<p><hi rend="print">Statement of Sales of</hi> Darwin’s Origin of Species<ref target="#foot.f1"/> <hi rend="print">to 1st</hi> Feby <hi rend="print">186</hi>7 <hi rend="print">by D. APPLETON &amp; CO., for account of</hi> Asa Gray <hi rend="print">On hand last account,</hi> 290 <hi rend="print">On hand this date,</hi> 148 <hi rend="print">Printed since,</hi> 100 <hi rend="print">Given away,</hi></p>
<p><hi rend="print">Sold to date,</hi> 242</p>
<p>390 390 <hi rend="print">Sold</hi> 242 <hi rend="print">Copies.</hi> $2<hi rend="superscript">50</hi> <hi rend="print">Rate</hi> 5% <hi rend="print">$</hi>30.25</p>
<p>Bal Jany 1/66 85.61</p>
<p>$115.86</p> </figure> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The presence of the statement in the Darwin Archive–CUL indicates that Gray sent it to CD; Gray sent the previous year’s statement as well, and may have enclosed it with his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5160.xml">letter of 18 July 1866</ref> (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 14). CD sent a letter to Gray on 28 February 1867 that has not been found (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5462.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Asa Gray, 26 March 1867</ref>), and Gray may have included the statement in a letter to CD of early February that also has not been found. For more on the sale of the US edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref>, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 14, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5081.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Asa Gray, 7 May 1866</ref> and n. 3.</note>
        </div>        
            
